    <div id=3D"node-1049" class=3D"node node-algorithm clearfix" about=3D"/=
dsa/graph-adjacency-list" typeof=3D"sioc:Item foaf:Document">

 =20
      <span property=3D"dc:title" content=3D"Adjacency List" class=3D"rdf-m=
eta element-hidden"></span>
 =20
  <div class=3D"content">
      <p id=3D"introduction">An adjacency list represents a graph as an arr=
ay of linked lists. The index of the array represents a vertex and each ele=
ment in its linked list represents the other vertices that form an edge wit=
h the vertex.</p>

<p>For example, we have a graph below.</p>

<figure><img alt=3D"A graph" height=3D"242" src=3D"https://www.programiz.co=
m/sites/tutorial2program/files/adjacency-list-graph.png" title=3D"A graph" =
width=3D"242">
	<figcaption>An undirected graph</figcaption>
</figure>

<p>We can represent this graph in the form of a linked list on a computer a=
s shown below.</p>

<figure><img alt=3D"Linked list representation of the graph" height=3D"304"=
 src=3D"https://www.programiz.com/sites/tutorial2program/files/adjacency-li=
st-representation.png" title=3D"Linked list representation of the graph" wi=
dth=3D"545">
	<figcaption>Linked list representation of the graph</figcaption>
</figure>

<p>Here, <strong>0</strong>, <strong>1</strong>, <strong>2</strong>, <stron=
g>3</strong> are the vertices and each of them forms a linked list with all=
 of its adjacent vertices. For instance, vertex 1 has two adjacent vertices=
 0 and 2. Therefore, 1 is linked with 0 and 2 in the figure above.</p>

<hr>
<h2 id=3D"pros">Pros of Adjacency List</h2>

<ul>
	<li>An adjacency list is efficient in terms of storage because we only nee=
d to store the values for the edges. For a sparse graph with millions of ve=
rtices and edges, this can mean a lot of saved space.</li>
	<li>It also helps to find all the vertices adjacent to a vertex easily.</l=
i>
</ul>

<hr>
<h2 id=3D"cons">Cons of Adjacency List</h2>

<ul>
	<li>Finding the adjacent list is not quicker than the adjacency matrix bec=
ause all the connected nodes must be first explored to find them.</li>
</ul>

<hr>
<h2 id=3D"structure">Adjacency List Structure</h2>

<p>The simplest adjacency list needs a node data structure to store a verte=
x and a graph data structure to organize the nodes.</p>

<p>We stay close to the basic definition of a graph - a collection of verti=
ces and edges <code>{V, E}</code>. For simplicity, we use an unlabeled grap=
h as opposed to a labeled one i.e. the vertices are identified by their ind=
ices 0,1,2,3.</p>

<p>Let's dig into the data structures at play here.</p>

<pre style=3D"max-height: 600px;"><code class=3D"dsa hljs cpp"><span class=
=3D"hljs-class"><span class=3D"hljs-keyword">struct</span> <span class=3D"h=
ljs-title">node</span>{</span>
    <span class=3D"hljs-keyword">int</span> vertex;
    <span class=3D"hljs-class"><span class=3D"hljs-keyword">struct</span> <=
span class=3D"hljs-title">node</span>* <span class=3D"hljs-title">next</spa=
n>;</span>
};

<span class=3D"hljs-class"><span class=3D"hljs-keyword">struct</span> <span=
 class=3D"hljs-title">Graph</span>{</span>
    <span class=3D"hljs-keyword">int</span> numVertices;
    <span class=3D"hljs-class"><span class=3D"hljs-keyword">struct</span> <=
span class=3D"hljs-title">node</span>** <span class=3D"hljs-title">adjLists=
</span>;</span>
};</code></pre>

<p></p><div id=3D"block-inject-1" class=3D"block-inject block-inject-1">
